cache."},"274":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"page","content":"Quickstart","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Guides","Guides"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart"},"275":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-0","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"Get a Yieldless application flow working with tuple errors, cancellation, and one realistic boundary."},"276":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-1","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#install","content":"Install"},"277":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-2","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"Step 1: stop throwing for routine failures"},"278":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-3","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"Step 2: group related work under one cancellation signal"},"279":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-4","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-3-add-retries-where-the-outside-world-is-unreliable","content":"Step 3: add retries where the outside world is unreliable"},"280":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-5","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"Step 4: keep the edges boring"},"281":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-6","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#a-full-request-flow","content":"A full request flow"},"282":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-7","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Where to go next"},"283":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-8","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#common-mistakes","content":"Common mistakes"},"284":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-9","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#good-keep-tuple-boundaries-explicit","content":"Good: keep tuple boundaries explicit"},"285":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-10","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#avoid-carrying-tuples-through-every-layer","content":"Avoid: carrying tuples through every layer"},"286":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-11","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#good-pass-cancellation-into-real-io","content":"Good: pass cancellation into real I/O"},"287":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-12","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#avoid-expecting-yieldless-to-stop-work-that-ignores-signals","content":"Avoid: expecting Yieldless to stop work that ignores signals"},"288":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-13","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"The fastest way to understand Yieldless is to wire the core pieces together:"},"289":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-14","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"`yieldless/error` to keep failures in tuple form"},"290":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-15","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"`yieldless/result` when tuple branches need light composition"},"291":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-16","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"`yieldless/task`, `yieldless/all`, `yieldless/iterable`, `yieldless/queue`, `yieldless/pubsub`, and `yieldless/limiter` to fan work out, hand it off, and control pressure"},"292":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-17","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"`yieldless/retry`, `yieldless/schedule`, `yieldless/signal`, `yieldless/timer`, and `yieldless/breaker` for resilient async boundaries"},"293":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-18","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"`yieldless/cache`, `yieldless/batcher`, and `yieldless/singleflight` for repeated, keyed, and duplicate work"},"294":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-19","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart","content":"Boundary adapters like `yieldless/fetch`, `yieldless/schema`, `yieldless/router`, `yieldless/ipc`, `yieldless/node`, and `yieldless/env`"},"295":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-20","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#install","content":"TypeScript 5.5+ is the target baseline. The package is compiled with `isolatedDeclarations` enabled."},"296":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-21","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"`safeTry()` and `safeTrySync()` let you treat common failures as data instead of exception control flow."},"297":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-22","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"That pattern is the center of the library. Every module is designed to fit back into the same `[error, value]` shape."},"298":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-23","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"When a tuple flow grows past one branch, use `yieldless/result` to keep it readable."},"299":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-24","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"Keep this modest. If one `if (error)` branch is clearer, use the branch."},"300":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-25","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"`runTaskGroup()` gives you a shared abort signal and sibling failure propagation."},"301":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-26","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"If `readRefs()` throws, the group aborts the shared signal, waits for `readStatus()` to settle, and then rethrows the original failure.\nIf the request or UI flow already has an `AbortSignal`, pass it in so the whole group inherits upstream cancellation."},"302":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-27","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"When the work is a list rather than a few named tasks, use `mapLimit()` to keep pressure on the outside world under control."},"303":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-28","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"The result order matches the input order, and the first tuple error aborts the remaining in-flight work."},"304":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-29","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"For async streams or generators, reach for `yieldless/iterable` instead of materializing everything first."},"305":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-30","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-3-add-retries-where-the-outside-world-is-unreliable","content":"Retries should stay close to transport boundaries: HTTP, queues, database connections, and subprocesses that can legitimately fail for transient reasons."},"306":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-31","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-3-add-retries-where-the-outside-world-is-unreliable","content":"The retry loop respects `AbortSignal`, so if a parent task group is canceled, the pending backoff timer is canceled too."},"307":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-32","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"When a boundary needs a firm time budget, derive one signal and pass it through the whole call chain."},"308":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-33","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"If you are calling HTTP JSON APIs, `yieldless/fetch` combines the same ideas:"},"309":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-34","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"If you need to wait for eventual consistency, use `poll()` instead of hand-writing timers."},"310":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-35","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"The package ships helpers for common backend boundaries and production pressure:"},"311":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-36","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/env` validates startup configuration"},"312":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-37","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/fetch` wraps HTTP status, JSON parsing, and deadlines"},"313":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-38","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/schema` keeps validators in tuple form"},"314":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-39","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/router` turns tuple handlers into HTTP responses"},"315":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-40","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/ipc` preserves tuple results across Electron IPC"},"316":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-41","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/node` wraps filesystem and child-process work"},"317":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-42","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/event` waits for one event with cleanup and abort support"},"318":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-43","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/schedule` builds reusable retry and repeat policies"},"319":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-44","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/limiter` protects shared capacity with semaphores and rate limits"},"320":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-45","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/queue` and `yieldless/pubsub` coordinate in-process workers and subscribers"},"321":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-46","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/cache` keeps successful read-through loads fresh for a TTL"},"322":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-47","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/batcher` collapses nearby keyed reads into ordered batches"},"323":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-48","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/breaker` backs off dependencies that are already failing"},"324":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-49","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/singleflight` deduplicates duplicate in-flight work"},"325":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-50","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"`yieldless/test` makes promises, clocks, and abort signals deterministic in tests"},"326":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-51","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Read Examples when you want copy-pasteable small patterns and a few larger compositions."},"327":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-52","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Read Module Selection when you are deciding which helper fits a specific problem."},"328":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-53","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Read Design Rules before you spread the tuple style across a large codebase."},"329":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-54","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Read Do and Don't if you are moving a team onto the library and want the conventions to stay sharp."},"330":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-55","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#where-to-go-next","content":"Use the reference section when you already know what module you need."},"331":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-56","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#avoid-carrying-tuples-through-every-layer","content":"Most UI and domain code wants ordinary values or ordinary state. Convert at the boundary."},"332":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"page","content":"Bounded Batch Work","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work"},"333":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","content":"Process lists of API, filesystem, or subprocess work without unbounded parallelism."},"334":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#refresh-several-repositories","content":"Refresh several repositories"},"335":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"Why this is friendlier"},"336":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#good-variation-stream-the-input","content":"Good variation: stream the input"},"337":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#avoid-unbounded-fan-out","content":"Avoid: unbounded fan-out"},"338":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","content":"This recipe is for the common \"do this for every item\" path: refresh every repo, fetch every avatar, resize every image, or inspect every file. The work is independent, but starting it all at once can make a user's machine or an upstream service miserable."},"339":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","content":"Use `mapLimit()` when you want tuple errors, shared cancellation, stable output order, and a hard ceiling on active work."},"340":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"Output order matches `repositories`, so UI code does not need to sort the result back into place."},"341":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"The first tuple error aborts in-flight work and stops starting new items."},"342":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"A parent `AbortSignal` can cancel the whole batch when the user navigates away."},"343":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"`concurrency` is explicit, so expensive work stays polite by default."},"344":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#good-variation-stream-the-input","content":"If repositories come from an async source, use `yieldless/iterable` instead of building a large array first."},"345":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#avoid-unbounded-fan-out","content":"That can launch dozens or hundreds of subprocesses. Use `mapLimit()` or `mapAsyncLimit()` so the user’s machine stays responsive."},"346":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"page","content":"Electron Git Client","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client"},"347":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","content":"An end-to-end shape for a desktop Git app using IPC tuples, abortable subprocesses, and typed renderer calls."},"348":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#main-process-contract","content":"Main-process contract"},"349":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#main-process-implementation","content":"Main-process implementation"},"350":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#preload-bridge","content":"Preload bridge"},"351":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#renderer-usage","content":"Renderer usage"},"352":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"Why this boundary feels cleaner"},"353":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#good-additions","content":"Good additions"},"354":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#avoid","content":"Avoid"},"355":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","content":"Yieldless fits Electron well because the important boundaries in an Electron app are all failure-heavy: the renderer asks for work through IPC, the main process touches the filesystem, the main process launches long-running child processes like `git clone`."},"356":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#main-process-implementation","content":"If the window is torn down or a parent task group is canceled, the subprocess is aborted through Node's native child-process signal handling."},"357":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"The renderer never depends on Electron's lossy thrown-error conversion."},"358":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"The main process can use the same tuple style it uses everywhere else."},"359":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"Long-running Git subprocesses can be canceled as soon as the UI no longer cares about them."},"360":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#good-additions","content":"Deduplicate status reads if several panels can request the same repository at once."},"361":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#good-additions","content":"Wait for one app or window event with cleanup."},"362":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#avoid","content":"Do not expose arbitrary IPC channels to the renderer."},"363":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#avoid","content":"Build a small preload bridge with `createIpcBridge()` or `createAbortableIpcBridge()` so the renderer only sees the operations it is allowed to call."},"364":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"page","content":"Electron PR Review Workbench","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench"},"365":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"A practical architecture for a GitHub pull-request review desktop app using tuples in the right places and ordinary UI state in the renderer."},"366":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-contract","content":"Main-process contract"},"367":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"Main-process implementation"},"368":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#preload-bridge","content":"Preload bridge"},"369":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#renderer-state","content":"Renderer state"},"370":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#why-this-fits-pr-review-tools-well","content":"Why this fits PR review tools well"},"371":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#good-additions","content":"Good additions"},"372":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#avoid","content":"Avoid"},"373":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#rule-of-thumb","content":"Rule of thumb"},"374":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"If you are building a GitHub PR review app in Electron, Yieldless fits best in the main process, preload bridge, and service layer. It is less useful as the shape of your React component state."},"375":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"That distinction matters:"},"376":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"Use tuples while you are still doing failure-heavy work: GitHub API calls, local Git reads, diff parsing, cache reads, IPC boundaries."},"377":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"Once the renderer receives the result, fold it into ordinary screen state and move on."},"378":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"The important thing here is not the exact helper list. It is the layering:"},"379":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"`yieldless/error` keeps the boundary readable with `ok()` and `err()`."},"380":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"`yieldless/all` loads the PR payload in parallel."},"381":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"`yieldless/task` gives the whole request one shared cancellation signal."},"382":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-17","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"`yieldless/node` keeps Git subprocess failures in the same tuple contract."},"383":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-18","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#renderer-state","content":"This is the point where Yieldless should usually stop being the dominant shape."},"384":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-19","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#renderer-state","content":"That keeps the renderer normal. Components render `idle`, `loading`, `ready`, or `error`. They do not need to carry `[error, value]` through every prop."},"385":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-20","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#why-this-fits-pr-review-tools-well","content":"Pull-request work crosses many noisy boundaries: GitHub HTTP, local Git, caches, and Electron IPC."},"386":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-21","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#why-this-fits-pr-review-tools-well","content":"Cancellation matters because users jump between PRs quickly and the old load should stop being important."},"387":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-22","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#why-this-fits-pr-review-tools-well","content":"The renderer wants stable view state, not a low-level transport shape."},"388":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-23","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#good-additions","content":"Deduplicate duplicate PR loads while a user is switching tabs or refreshing panels."},"389":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-24","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#good-additions","content":"Use bounded iterable work when processing many files in a diff."},"390":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-25","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#avoid","content":"Do not keep tuples as your component model."},"391":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-26","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#avoid","content":"Fold the tuple once into `idle`, `loading`, `ready`, and `error` state. UI code should speak in screen states."},"392":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-27","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#rule-of-thumb","content":"Use Yieldless in the main process and preload boundary."},"393":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-28","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#rule-of-thumb","content":"Convert tuples into domain state at the renderer edge."},"394":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-29","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#rule-of-thumb","content":"Do not force tuple results deep into component trees."},"395":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"page","content":"Repository Indexer","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer"},"396":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"A larger example that combines queues, pub/sub, caching, batching, limits, retries, task groups, and Node subprocesses."},"397":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#the-indexer","content":"The indexer"},"398":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#using-it-from-a-route-or-action","content":"Using it from a route or action"},"399":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"Why this is easier to operate"},"400":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#smaller-variations","content":"Smaller variations"},"401":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#process-a-fixed-list-without-a-long-running-queue","content":"Process a fixed list without a long-running queue"},"402":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#keep-only-the-cache-and-batcher","content":"Keep only the cache and batcher"},"403":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#add-a-circuit-breaker-to-an-optional-dependency","content":"Add a circuit breaker to an optional dependency"},"404":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#avoid-hiding-the-pipeline-inside-a-generic-worker-framework","content":"Avoid: hiding the pipeline inside a generic worker framework"},"405":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"This recipe shows a realistic in-process worker pipeline: a user selects repositories, the app indexes them, progress is streamed to the UI, remote metadata is cached, owner lookups are batched, and local Git subprocesses stay bounded."},"406":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"The point is not to build a new runtime. The point is to keep the moving parts visible:"},"407":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/queue` accepts work with backpressure"},"408":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/pubsub` broadcasts progress"},"409":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/task` runs workers under one cancellation signal"},"410":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/limiter` protects API quota and local subprocess capacity"},"411":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/cache` avoids repeated metadata reads"},"412":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/batcher` collapses nearby owner lookups"},"413":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-17","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/retry` handles transient remote failures"},"414":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-18","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/fetch` keeps remote calls in tuple form"},"415":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-19","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/node` wraps local Git commands as tuples"},"416":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-20","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#using-it-from-a-route-or-action","content":"In a real UI, the progress subscription often lives in a websocket, server-sent events stream, or Electron IPC handler. The shape stays the same: subscribe, render events, and abort when the user leaves."},"417":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-21","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"The queue is bounded, so user-selected work cannot grow memory forever."},"418":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-22","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"Worker count is explicit, so local Git subprocesses stay polite."},"419":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-23","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"API quota waits happen before remote calls, not after the upstream complains."},"420":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-24","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"Metadata reads are cached, but failed reads are not stored."},"421":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-25","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"Owner lookups batch together while still returning one result per job."},"422":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-26","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"Retry policy sits around the flaky remote read, not around the whole pipeline."},"423":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-27","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"Progress is just an async subscription, so it can feed logs, UI, or tests."},"424":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-28","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#process-a-fixed-list-without-a-long-running-queue","content":"If you already have the whole list and do not need progress fanout, `mapLimit()` is smaller."},"425":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-29","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#keep-only-the-cache-and-batcher","content":"If the pipeline is overkill, keep the read model helpers."},"426":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-30","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#add-a-circuit-breaker-to-an-optional-dependency","content":"If indexing can continue without feature flags or recommendations, wrap that optional remote call with a circuit breaker and use a fallback when it is open."},"427":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-31","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#avoid-hiding-the-pipeline-inside-a-generic-worker-framework","content":"That looks shorter, but the operational choices disappear. Yieldless works best when the important limits remain close to the work they protect."},"428":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"page","content":"Resilient Service Flow","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow"},"429":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","content":"A practical backend flow that combines tuples, retries, validation, routing, and cancellation."},"430":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"The moving parts"},"431":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#route-handler","content":"Route handler"},"432":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#why-this-holds-up-well-in-production","content":"Why this holds up well in production"},"433":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#good-variation-add-a-remote-dependency","content":"Good variation: add a remote dependency"},"434":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#avoid-retrying-the-whole-handler","content":"Avoid: retrying the whole handler"},"435":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#rules-worth-keeping","content":"Rules worth keeping"},"436":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","content":"This recipe shows the shape Yieldless is best at: an HTTP request that validates input, performs a few pieces of I/O, retries the flaky part, and returns a normal JSON response."},"437":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/schema` validates input without throwing"},"438":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/fetch` keeps HT